VLAN:
=====
what is VLAN:
 - A vlan is way to split one big network into smaller groups,
   without using extra physical cables.

why do we need VLAN:
 Imagine this situation:
    > HR team
    > Engineering team
    > Finance team
    All are connected to the same network switch.

    Problem: *without VLAN:
    > Everyone can see everyone's network traffic.
    > Less security
    > Too much traffic (slow network)

    Solution: *with VLAN:
    > HR stays in HR network (VLAN 10)
    > Engineering stays in Engineering network (VLAN 20)
    > Finance stays in Finance network (VLAN 30)
    Now, same switch, but logically separated networks.

    Real-example:
    > One building (switch)
    > Different floors (VLANs))

    People from:
    > Floor 1 cannot enter floor 2 without permission (VLAN isolation)
    > But all floors are in the same building (same physical switch)

What VLAN actually does:
------------------------
1) Separates traffic (like different rooms in a house)
2) Improves security (sensitive data stays within it's VLAN))
3) Reduces network congestion (less broadcast traffic)
4) Easy to manage (group users by function, not location)

How VLAN works:
---------------
1) you have one switch
2) you assign ports to different VLANs:
   port 1,2 --> VLAN 10 (HR)
    port 3,4 --> VLAN 20 (Engineering)
    port 4 ----> VLAN 30 (Finance)
3) Devices in same VLAN can talk to each other directly.
4) Devices in different VLANs cannot communicate talk directly (without router).
5) * they need a router or layer 3 switch to talk between VLANs.


> VLAN stands for virtual local area network.
> Vlans logically segment a physical network into multiple isolated networks.
> Devices in the same vlan can communicate directly, even if they are on different switches.
> Devices in different VLANS need a router or layer 3 switch to communicate.
> VLANs improve security by isolating sensitive traffic (HR vs Engineering)
> VLANs reduce broadcast traffic, improving network performance.
> Each VLAN is identified by unique VLAN ID (1-4094).
> Access port are assigned to a single VLAN for end devices (e.g, cisco (switchport access vlan 10))
> Trunk ports carry traffic for multiple VLANs between switches (e.g, cisco (switchport mode trunk))
> VLAN tagging (e.g, IEEE 802.1Q) adds a VLAN ID to Ethernet frames on trunk links.

Example:
--------
VLAN 10: HR Department
VLAN 20: Engineering Department
VLAN 30: Guest Network
VLAN 99: Management Network

(above vlans cannot see each other's traffic)
(if want see each other, need a router or layer 3 switch)

> VLANS allow flexible network design without changing physical cabling.
> Voice VLANs can be used to separate IP phone traffic from data traffic.
> Guest VLANS isolate visitor devices from internal network resources.
> Management VLANS restrict access to network devices for administrators only.


Diagram:
========
                +-------------------+
                |     Switch        |
                +-------------------+
                | Port 1  | VLAN 10 |---- HR PC1
                | Port 2  | VLAN 10 |---- HR PC2
                | Port 3  | VLAN 20 |---- Eng PC1
                | Port 4  | VLAN 20 |---- Eng PC2
                | Port 5  | VLAN 30 |---- Guest Laptop
                | Port 6  | VLAN 99 |---- Admin PC
                | Port 7  | Trunk   |==== To another switch (carries all VLANs)
                +-------------------+

Legend:
- Devices in the same VLAN (e.g., HR PC1 & HR PC2) can talk to each other.
- Devices in different VLANs (e.g., HR PC1 & Eng PC1) cannot communicate directly.
- Trunk port connects switches and carries multiple VLANs.

VLAN/TRUNK PORT/ACCESS PORT:
============================
VLAN: Virtual Lan: isolates broadcast domains
Trunk Port: Carries multiple VLAN
Access Port: Carries traffic for one VLAN

















































